{{astrodynamics}}
== The Kepler Problem == While Kepler's equation is easy to solve for time, there is no general solution for the reverse problem. To determine eccentric anomaly (and thus spacecraft position) at a given time, generally an iterative numerical method is used, such as Newton's method: :<math> x_{k+1}=x_{k}-\frac{F(x_k)}{F'(x_k)}</math> Where :<math>F(E) = E - e \sin(E) - M(t)</math> The iteration takes the form :<math>E_{k+1}=E_{k} - \frac{ E_{k} - e \sin(E_{k}) - M(t) }{ 1 - e \cos(E_{k})}</math> For most elliptical orbits an initial guess of ''E<sub>0</sub>'' = ''M'' is sufficient; for orbits with eccentricities greater than 0.8, ''E<sub>0</sub>'' = &pi; may be used. Better initial guesses are possible, but are not generally required. The iterative process is repeated until required accuracy conditions are achieved, for example: :<math> |E_{k+1}-E_k|<\delta</math> Where &delta; is the desired accuracy.
== Numerical Solution ==

